{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}
'''Edward Lamar Hopson''' (born June 30, 1971) is a former professional [[boxing|boxer]].

==Amateur career==
Born in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], Hopson took up boxing at the age of seven. Hopson earned a [[AAU Junior Olympic Games|Junior Olympics]] gold medal in 1987, and was the [[National Golden Gloves Featherweight Champion]] the following year.<ref>{{cite news|last=Berger|first=Phil|title=Olympic Profile: Ed Hopson; A Quick Study Is Moving Up Fast|work=The New York Times|date=1988-07-10|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/07/10/sports/olympic-profile-ed-hopson-a-quick-study-is-moving-up-fast.html|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref> Later in 1988, he won the Olympic Trials in the featherweight division; after a semifinal victory against [[World Amateur Boxing Championships|world amateur champion]] [[Kelcie Banks]], Hopson took a 3–2 decision over [[Carl Daniels]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Schuyler Jr.|first=Ed|title=Hopson claims 125-pound title|work=The Times-News|agency=Associated Press|date=1988-07-11|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=ihsaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=XSQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2939,2487289|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref> However, at the Olympic Boxoffs, Hopson lost to Banks in a pair of fights; because of these losses, he did not compete in the [[Boxing at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Hamelin|first=Joe|title=Hopson knew it|work=The Modesto Bee|date=1988-07-18|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=hkcjAAAAIBAJ&sjid=jswFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1557,5449138|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref>

==Professional career==
Known as "Fast" Eddie, Hopson turned pro in 1989 and captured the vacant [[International Boxing Federation]] [[super featherweight]] title in 1995 with a [[knockout]] win over Moises Pedroza.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. Leads Austria in Fed Cup|work=Los Angeles Times|date=1995-04-23|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1995-04-23/sports/sp-57875_1_fed-cup/2|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref> He lost the belt in his first defense, to [[Tracy Harris Patterson]], later that year by 2nd round technical knockout (TKO), a round in which Hopson had four knockdowns recorded against him.<ref>{{cite news|title=Patterson stops Hopson|work=Sun Journal|agency=Associated Press|date=1995-07-10|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=WtcgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=DGsFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5106,1469872|accessdate=2010-07-01}}</ref> Shortly afterward, Hopson lost via TKO to Santos Lopez and retired.

He had a brief comeback in 1998 but retired for good in 1999.

